Segmentation Insights: Navigating User Paths for Better Conversions
¶

by Crystal Huang
Data Mining, Discovery, and Exploration
Harvard Extension School
Spring 2025

1. Executive Summary¶

This project uses Google Analytics 4 (GA4) e-commerce data from the Google Merchandise Store for December 2020 to address two interconnected business challenges: behavioral segmentation and user journey analysis. By segmenting users based on aggregated browsing and engagement patterns and analyzing navigation flows, this study aims to provide actionable insights for targeted marketing, enhanced user experiences, and improved conversion rates.

E-commerce platforms like the Google Merchandise Store often struggle to understand how visitor behaviors vary and what patterns contribute to conversions or drop-offs. To address this, the project applies clustering algorithms to group users with similar behavioral profiles and graph-based models to analyze their navigation paths.

After exploring both session-level and user-level aggregation, the analysis focused on the user level to better capture consistent behavioral patterns across visits. Feature engineering, data transformation, dimensionality reduction, and a range of clustering techniques (K-Means, DBSCAN, and OPTICS) were used to uncover distinct user segments. Among these clustering methods, DBSCAN proved most effective, surfacing more nuanced clusters that closely reflected differences in user engagement.

To better understand what differentiates users who convert from those who don’t, a graph-based analysis of user journeys was run on key clusters. Comparing high-intent browsers to actual purchasers highlighted differences in navigation flows, points of friction, and how users interacted with features like wishlists and info pages. These patterns helped surface opportunities to improve the user experience and encourage more users to complete their path to purchase.

2. Data Overview¶

The project utilizes an updated version of the ga4_obfuscated_sample_ecommerce dataset available through the BigQuery Public Datasets program. This dataset contains obfuscated Google Analytics 4 (GA4) event export data from the Google Merchandise Store for December 2020. It captures detailed user interactions with the website, including product views, purchases, and engagement activities.

The cleaned event-level dataset consists of 1,071,172 events from 103,836 unique users across 120,420 sessions. It includes the following 11 columns:

Column Description
user_pseudo_id Anonymous unique identifier for users
ga_session_id Identifier for user sessions
event_timestamp Timestamp of the event
event_name Name of the event (e.g., page_view, purchase)
event_category Event category (passive,engagement,purchase)
cleaned_page_title Page title (cleaned)
page_category Page category (account_page, home_page, checkout_page, product_catalog_page, info_page, product_page, search_page, error_page, request_page, wishlist_page)
device_category Type of device (e.g., mobile, desktop)
device_mobile_brand_name Mobile device brand
geo_continent Continent of the user

Due to high cardinality and sparsity, the geo_country field was excluded from the cleaned dataset. Regional information was retained via the geo_continent variable to balance geographic context with dimensionality considerations. In addition, cleaning and categorization were applied to the event_category, cleaned_page_title, and page_category columns to reduce high cardinality and inconsistent granularity. These fields were grouped into broader, standardized categories using business logic to improve interpretability and support analysis.

        'Non-Null Count': df.count()
    })

    return df

3. Data Preparation and Exploration¶

3.1 Session-Level Feature Engineering (for Exploratory Analysis)¶

To support exploratory analysis, the cleaned event-level GA4 data was aggregated into a session-level dataset. Each row represents a single session and includes features capturing temporal patterns, engagement signals, and contextual attributes.

Temporal Features:

  • Converted timestamps and sorted events chronologically.
  • Calculated time gaps between events and average time per session.
  • Computed session duration, start hour, and day of week.

Engagement Features:

  • Counted total and unique events per session.
  • Summarized event categories (e.g., passive, engagement, purchase).
  • Counted page views by category (e.g., product, checkout).
  • Captured first/last events and landing/exit pages.

Contextual Features: Extracted device type, mobile brand, and geographic location from the first event.

This dataset was used for behavioral exploration and guided the construction of user-level features but was not included in clustering.

In [3]:
df_event = df.copy()
df_event['event_timestamp'] = pd.to_datetime(df_event['event_timestamp'])
df_event = df_event.sort_values(['user_pseudo_id', 'ga_session_id', 'event_timestamp'])

# Session-level features
df_event['time_diff'] = df_event.groupby(['user_pseudo_id', 'ga_session_id'])['event_timestamp'].diff().dt.total_seconds()
avg_time_between = df_event.groupby(['user_pseudo_id', 'ga_session_id'])['time_diff'] \
                     .mean().reset_index(name='avg_time_between_events')

session_times = df_event.groupby(['user_pseudo_id', 'ga_session_id']).agg(
    session_start=('event_timestamp', 'min'),
    session_end=('event_timestamp', 'max')
).reset_index()
session_times['session_duration'] = (session_times['session_end'] - session_times['session_start']).dt.total_seconds()
session_times['session_hour'] = session_times['session_start'].dt.hour
session_times['session_dayofweek'] = session_times['session_start'].dt.day_name()

# Engagement features
event_counts = df_event.groupby(['user_pseudo_id', 'ga_session_id']).agg(
    num_events_total=('event_name', 'count'),
    num_event_names=('event_name', 'nunique')
).reset_index()

event_types = df_event.groupby(['user_pseudo_id', 'ga_session_id', 'event_category'])['event_name'] \
                .count().unstack(fill_value=0).reset_index()
event_types = event_types.rename(columns=lambda x: f'num_{x}_events' if x not in ['user_pseudo_id', 'ga_session_id'] else x)

page_category_counts = df_event.groupby(['user_pseudo_id', 'ga_session_id', 'page_category'])['event_name'] \
                         .count().unstack(fill_value=0).reset_index()
page_category_counts = page_category_counts.rename(columns=lambda x: f'num_{x}_pages' if x not in ['user_pseudo_id', 'ga_session_id'] else x)

first_last_events = df_event.groupby(['user_pseudo_id', 'ga_session_id']).agg(
    first_event=('event_name', lambda x: x.iloc[0]),
    last_event=('event_name', lambda x: x.iloc[-1])
).reset_index()

# First and last page categories and titles
first_last_pages = df_event.groupby(['user_pseudo_id', 'ga_session_id']).agg(
    first_page_category=('page_category', lambda x: x.iloc[0]),
    last_page_category=('page_category', lambda x: x.iloc[-1]),
    first_page_title=('cleaned_page_title', lambda x: x.iloc[0]),
    last_page_title=('cleaned_page_title', lambda x: x.iloc[-1])
).reset_index()

# Contextual features
device_geo = df_event.groupby(['user_pseudo_id', 'ga_session_id']).agg(
    device_category=('device_category', 'first'),
    device_mobile_brand_name=('device_mobile_brand_name', 'first'),
    geo_continent=('geo_continent', 'first')).reset_index()

# Merge all feature sets into a session-level dataset
dfs_to_merge = [session_times, avg_time_between, 
                event_counts, event_types, page_category_counts, 
                first_last_events, first_last_pages, device_geo]

df_session = reduce(
    lambda left, right: pd.merge(left, right, on=['user_pseudo_id', 'ga_session_id'], how='left'),
    dfs_to_merge
)

# Impute missing avg_time_between_events (typically for single-event sessions)
df_session['avg_time_between_events'] = df_session['avg_time_between_events'].fillna(0)

3.2 Session Behavioral Patterns and Temporal Trends¶

While clustering was performed at the user level, session-level exploration provided important context on how users interacted with the site. This section highlights key behavioral trends and temporal dynamics observed across sessions.

A. Event Distributions¶

Session-level activity was examined through total event counts, event types, and landing and exit pages.

Most sessions had fewer than 20 events, but a small number showed much higher activity, which could point to deeper engagement. Passive events made up the bulk of user actions, while engagement and purchase events were far less common. This is typical for an e-commerce site with low overall conversion.

Landing and exit page distributions revealed that most sessions started and ended on product catalog, home, or product pages. Checkout pages were common exit points for converting sessions.

B. Engagement Level Analysis¶

Sessions were classified into three engagement levels:

  • Purchaser: At least one purchase event
  • Engaged: Engagement events but no purchases
  • Passive: Neither engagement nor purchase events
In [6]:

    lambda row: 'Purchaser' if row.get('num_purchase_events', 0) > 0
    else 'Engaged' if row.get('num_engagement_events', 0) > 0
    else 'Passive', axis=1
)

Most sessions were passive, with fewer users engaging or making purchases. Purchaser sessions stood out not only for being longer but also for involving a wider variety of events, while passive sessions tended to include only a few. Engaged sessions fell somewhere in between. Device type appeared to have minimal impact on engagement level distribution.

3.3 User-Level Aggregation¶

To capture more consistent behavioral patterns and reduce session-level variability, features were aggregated at the user level. For each user, session metrics were summarized using the mean, and engagement signals were totaled across all sessions.

In addition to numeric aggregation, each user was assigned an engagement level label based on their cumulative activity, following the same definitions introduced in the previous section. This label was used later for interpreting cluster patterns but not included as an input in the clustering model.

The resulting dataset provided a consolidated view of user behavior across sessions and served as the foundation for clustering and modeling.

    return series.mode().iloc[0] if not series.mode().empty else np.nan

Most of the features were heavily right-skewed, with values packed near zero and a few extreme outliers. This was especially true for event-related counts like purchases, engagements, and product catalog views. Features like session duration and time between events also had long tails. Others, like the number of unique events or sessions, showed more stepped or discrete patterns. Overall, the distributions suggested that transformation would be helpful before clustering, both to reduce skew and to make the features more comparable.

3.5 Variable Transformation¶

Most user-level features were non-negative but included a number of zeros, which made log transformation unsuitable. Instead, a Yeo-Johnson transformation was applied using scikit-learn’s power_transform, which handles zero values and helps bring distributions closer to normal. This step improves the feature space for clustering by reducing skew and making the scales more comparable. Features with extreme sparsity (more than 70 percent zeros) were excluded prior to transformation, since the method is less effective when most values are zero.

In [13]:
def prepare_clustering_data(df_user, clustering_features, metadata_features):
    """
    Transforms selected features using Yeo-Johnson and returns:
    - Transformed feature matrix (X_transformed)
    - Result DataFrame with metadata and transformed features (df_result)
    """
    X_raw = df_user[clustering_features].copy()
    X_transformed = power_transform(X_raw, method='yeo-johnson')

    df_transformed = pd.DataFrame(X_transformed, columns=clustering_features, index=df_user.index)
    df_result = pd.concat([df_user[metadata_features].copy(), df_transformed], axis=1)

    return X_transformed, df_result
In [14]:
metadata_features = ['user_pseudo_id', 'engagement_level','first_page_category', 'last_page_category']

X_transformed, df_result = prepare_clustering_data(df_user, clustering_features, metadata_features)

3.6 Transformation Diagnostics¶

The effect of the Yeo-Johnson transformation was evaluated using histograms, CDFs, and Q-Q plots. Most features became more balanced and comparable in scale, making them better suited for clustering. A few showed little change, which was expected given their distribution.

    ax = axs.flat[i]
    sns.histplot(X_transformed[:, i], kde=True, ax=ax)
    ax.set_title(f'Transformed: {col}')
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

The figure above shows the distributions of all selected features after applying the Yeo-Johnson transformation. While some features still showed discrete or clustered values (i.e. num_purchase_events, num_event_names), most became more symmetric and better scaled. To take a closer look, a few representative features were examined using CDF and Q-Q plots to evaluate how well the transformation improved normality and spread.

Looking at the CDF and Q-Q plots for selected features:

  • session_duration showed a smooth cumulative spread, and its Q-Q plot indicated better alignment with a normal distribution, especially through the midrange.

  • num_purchase_events, while still sparse, showed value compression in the CDF. The Q-Q plot reflected the challenge of normalizing such skewed data, but the feature was kept for its strong behavioral relevance and potential to help identify high-value users.

Overall, the transformation helped reduce skew and brought most features closer to a scale more suitable for clustering.

3.7 Dimensionality Reduction¶

To explore the structure of the data before clustering, UMAP was applied to the transformed features and reduced them to 15 dimensions. This helped retain more of the underlying relationships between users while simplifying the input space.

Two distance metrics were tested:

  • Euclidean (default): works well when features are scaled and balanced

  • Cosine: captures directional similarity in behavior, which can be useful for comparing usage patterns

In [17]:
def umap_embedding(X, n_components=15, metric='euclidean', random_state=4365):
    reducer = umap.UMAP(n_components=n_components, metric=metric, random_state=random_state)
    return reducer.fit_transform(X)

X_umap_euclidean = umap_embedding(X_transformed)
X_umap_cosine = umap_embedding(X_transformed, metric='cosine')

For visualization, 2D projections were also created using both metrics to see if any natural groupings emerged.

In the Euclidean projection, Purchasers are fairly well separated from the other two groups, while Passive and Engaged users have more overlap. In the cosine projection, the overall distance between groups appears greater, with less overlap between Passive and Engaged. 3.8 Key Findings Informing Modeling¶

The exploratory analysis and dimensionality reduction surfaced several patterns that shaped the modeling approach. Purchasers and engaged users typically had longer sessions, interacted more frequently, and showed greater behavioral diversity. While the majority of users were passive, higher-value users stood out with stronger engagement signals—both in the raw behavioral metrics and in the UMAP projections.

These findings suggest that meaningful behavioral segmentation is possible, and helped guide decisions around feature selection and clustering methods in the next stage.

4. Modeling Approach¶

Building on patterns observed during exploration, the next phase focused on clustering users based on their aggregated behavioral features. The goal was to uncover meaningful segments that could support personalized marketing strategies and improve the user experience. Several clustering algorithms were applied to explore different grouping structures and check for consistency across methods.

4.1 K-Means Clustering¶

K-Means was chosen as a starting point due to its simplicity and efficiency in handling well-scaled, numeric data. Since the features were transformed to reduce skew and bring them to comparable scales, the assumptions of K-Means were reasonably well met. To evaluate different values of k, WCSS, BCSS, silhouette score, and the Calinski-Harabasz index were computed and plotted. These helped assess the compactness and separation of clusters and guided the selection of a reasonable k for modeling.

In [19]:
def cluster_search_kmeans(df, nclusts=(2,21), n_init=10):
    ## If there are cluster assignments in the data frame remove them. 
    if 'kmeans_cluster' in df.columns: df.drop(columns='kmeans_cluster', inplace=True)
    WCSS=[]
    BCSS=[]
    silhouette=[]
    CH_index = []
    ## Compute total sum of squares
    x_bar = np.mean(df, axis=0)
    TSS = np.sum(np.sum(np.square(df - x_bar)))
    for n in range(nclusts[0],nclusts[1]+1):   
        temp_model = KMeans(n_clusters=n, n_init=n_init).fit(df)
        WCSS.append(temp_model.inertia_)
        BCSS.append(TSS - temp_model.inertia_)
        assignments = temp_model.predict(df)
        silhouette.append(silhouette_score(df, assignments))
        CH_index.append(calinski_harabasz_score(df, assignments))
    _, ax = plt.subplots(2,2, figsize=(8,8))    
    ax = ax.flatten()
    ax[0].plot(range(nclusts[0],nclusts[1]+1),WCSS)   
    ax[0].set_xlabel('Number of clusters')
    ax[0].set_ylabel('WCSS')
    ax[1].plot(range(nclusts[0],nclusts[1]+1),BCSS)   
    ax[1].set_xlabel('Number of clusters')
    ax[1].set_ylabel('BCSS')
    ax[2].plot(range(nclusts[0],nclusts[1]+1),silhouette)   
    ax[2].set_xlabel('Number of clusters')
    ax[2].set_ylabel('Silhouette Score')
    ax[3].plot(range(nclusts[0],nclusts[1]+1),CH_index)   
    ax[3].set_xlabel('Number of clusters')
    ax[3].set_ylabel('Calinski Harabasz Score')
In [20]:
X_clustering = pd.DataFrame(X_transformed, columns=clustering_features)

The most balanced choice for k appears to be 5. The WCSS curve shows a clear elbow at this point, while the BCSS rises quickly up to around k = 5 before leveling off. The silhouette score also increases more sharply near k = 5, and although the Calinski-Harabasz index peaks slightly earlier, it remains relatively high at k = 5 before starting to decline. Taken together, these trends suggest that five clusters offer a good trade-off between compactness, separation, and interpretability.

The cluster assignments from K-Means aligned reasonably well with the engagement-level categories. To explore that further, the next step is to try other clustering methods that might capture more nuanced patterns.

4.2 DBSCAN¶

Unlike K-Means, DBSCAN doesn't require specifying the number of clusters up front and can identify clusters of varying shapes and densities. It’s also useful for filtering out noise or outlier points that don’t belong to any cluster. Given that user behavior may not fall into clean, spherical groups, DBSCAN offers a more flexible approach to uncovering structure in the data.

To explore this, a small grid of eps and min_samples values was tested across both UMAP projections (Euclidean and Cosine), and clustering quality was evaluated using silhouette scores and noise levels.

In [ ]:
def evaluate_dbscan_model(X, umap_label, eps, min_samples, leaf_size=60):
    """Fits a DBSCAN model on the input data and evaluates clustering quality."""
    # Fit DBSCAN model
    model = DBSCAN(eps=eps, min_samples=min_samples, leaf_size=leaf_size)
    labels = model.fit_predict(X)

    # Count clusters and noise points
    n_clusters = len(set(labels)) - (1 if -1 in labels else 0)
    n_noise = list(labels).count(-1)

    # Filter out overly fragmented or empty clusterings
    if n_clusters > 50 or n_clusters == 0 or n_noise == len(labels):
        score = None
    else:
        score = silhouette_score(X, labels, sample_size=10000, random_state=42)
        
    # Return evaluation metrics
    return {
        'umap_space': umap_label,
        'eps': eps,
        'min_samples': min_samples,
        'leaf_size': leaf_size,
        'clusters': n_clusters,
        'noise': n_noise,
        'silhouette': score
    }
In [25]:
eps_range = [0.8, 1.0]
min_samples_range = [200, 250, 300]
leaf_size = 60

# Create list of delayed evaluation jobs for UMAP-Euclidean space
jobs = [
    delayed(evaluate_dbscan_model)(X_umap_euclidean, 'euclidean', eps, min_samples, leaf_size)
    for eps in eps_range for min_samples in min_samples_range
] + [
    # Append evaluation jobs for UMAP-Cosine space
    delayed(evaluate_dbscan_model)(X_umap_cosine, 'cosine', eps, min_samples, leaf_size)
    for eps in eps_range for min_samples in min_samples_range
]

# Run all DBSCAN jobs in parallel using 3 workers
results = Parallel(n_jobs=3, backend='loky')(tqdm(jobs, desc="Running DBSCAN grid search"))

df_dbscan_results = pd.DataFrame(results)

Like DBSCAN, OPTICS doesn't require a predefined number of clusters and can handle variable density.

4.4 Comparison and Evaluation of Clustering Methods¶

Among the three methods, DBSCAN was selected as the most effective clustering approach for this dataset. It achieved a silhouette score comparable to KMeans while revealing more granular structure within user behavior. It successfully isolated Purchasers into distinct clusters and showed clear groupings among Passive and Engaged users. Compared to OPTICS, DBSCAN produced fewer noise points and more balanced cluster sizes. Its flexibility in handling different densities and shapes of user behavior made it a better fit for segmentation and interpretation.

This helped surface meaningful distinctions in browsing depth and engagement style across clusters.

Clusters Takeaways¶

The top clusters within each engagement group highlight distinct patterns in user behavior, offering insight into where different users are in their journey and how they might be guided toward deeper engagement or conversion.

Purchaser Clusters

  • Cluster 4 (Deliberate Shoppers): Long sessions, higher time between events, and elevated counts across passive, engagement, and product catalog views. These users also triggered a wide range of events, suggesting exploratory behavior, likely browsing thoroughly before making a purchase.
  • Cluster 17 (Intentional Buyers): Shorter, more efficient sessions with fewer catalog views but still a high variety of events. These users were likely goal-driven and knew exactly what they wanted.

Engaged Clusters

  • Cluster 2 (Casual Browsers): Moderate session length with steady engagement, limited product catalog views, and balanced activity. These users show interest but don’t explore deeply.
  • Cluster 3 (High-Intent Browsers): Longer sessions with high engagement and broad interaction across the site. This group appears highly interested but didn’t convert, possibly still evaluating.
  • Cluster 9 (Drive-By Browsers): Short sessions with light engagement. These users likely came in to check something specific and left quickly—possibly returning users doing quick lookups.

Passive Clusters

  • Cluster 0 (Barely There): Very short sessions with minimal interaction. Likely casual visitors with little intent to explore or convert.
  • Cluster 1 (Window Shoppers): Similar to Cluster 0 but with more product catalog views—could be early-stage browsers or visitors landing on category pages.
  • Cluster 7 (Early Explorers): Slightly more event diversity than other passive users. Possibly users who began exploring but dropped off early.

On the other hand, groups like "Drive-By Browsers", "Casual Browsers", and "Early Explorers" showed more fragmented or shallow engagement, which may make them harder to convert without a more tailored approach.

4.6 Navigating User Journeys Between Browsing and Conversion¶

To build on the clustering results, this section compares navigation patterns between two key groups:

  • High-Intent Browsers (Cluster 3): Showed high engagement but no purchase
  • Deliberate Shoppers (Cluster 4): Converted after longer browsing sessions

The goal is to understand how user journeys differ between these groups by analyzing the pages they visit, the paths they follow, and where they tend to drop off. These insights can inform strategies to reduce friction, improve key touchpoints, and better support users in moving toward conversion.

fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(16, 8))
cluster_titles = {
    3: "High-Intent Browsers (Cluster 3)",
    4: "Deliberate Shoppers (Cluster 4)"
}
# Loop through each key cluster and create a navigation graph
for ax, cluster_num in zip(axes, [3, 4]):
    # Get only the rows for the current cluster and sort by user and time
    df_cluster = df_journey[df_journey['dbscan_cluster'] == cluster_num].sort_values(['user_pseudo_id', 'event_timestamp'])

    # Get the next page for each user (based on event order)
    df_cluster['next_page'] = df_cluster.groupby('user_pseudo_id')['page_category'].shift(-1)

    # Keep only valid transitions (no missing values, no duplicates like A -> A)
    transitions = df_cluster.dropna(subset=['page_category', 'next_page'])
    transitions = transitions[transitions['page_category'] != transitions['next_page']]

    # Get and sort transition counts
    transition_counts = transitions.groupby(['page_category', 'next_page']).size().reset_index(name='count')
    top_transitions = transition_counts.sort_values('count', ascending=False)
    
    # Create a directed graph and add edges based on transition counts
    G = nx.DiGraph() # Using DiGraph to show the arrows
    for _, row in top_transitions.iterrows():
        G.add_edge(row['page_category'], row['next_page'], weight=row['count'])
    
    pos = nx.spring_layout(G, k=0.7, seed=42)
    nx.draw_networkx(G, pos, ax=ax, with_labels=True, node_size=1200, font_size=9, arrows=True, alpha=0.85)
    ax.set_title(f'Navigation Graph - {cluster_titles[cluster_num]}')
    ax.axis('off')

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

Based on the user journey graphs, a few patterns stand out:

Common Ground: Both groups frequently visited core shopping pages like home_page, product_catalog_page, and product_page, reflecting similar interest in browsing and exploring products.

Deliberate Shoppers (Cluster 4): These users moved through the site in a more structured way and showed signs of purposeful behavior.

  • Their sessions followed a clear path through key shopping pages and into checkout.
  • They also used features like wishlist_page, account_page, and info_page, which likely helped them make a purchase decision.
  • Very few ended up on error_page, suggesting a smoother overall experience.

High-Intent Browsers (Cluster 3): These users demonstrated strong interest and explored deeply, reaching checkout pages but ultimately not converting.

  • They spent time on product and checkout pages, but didn’t convert.
  • More sessions hit error_page or request_page, which may point to friction or gaps in the experience.
  • Fewer visits to supporting pages like wishlist_page and info_page could also signal a lack of reinforcement at key points in their decision process.

5. Conclusion and Recommendations¶

This project explored how users interact with the site by grouping them based on behavioral patterns observed through session and user-level features. Using a mix of clustering techniques, including DBSCAN, K-Means, and OPTICS, the analysis surfaced clear segments ranging from casual visitors to highly engaged users and purchasers.

An important takeaway from this project was the critical role of data preparation when applying density-based clustering methods. Early attempts to run DBSCAN and OPTICS on the MinMax-scaled feature set consistently failed, often crashing the kernel due to the zero-inflated and skewed nature of the data, which led to instability in distance calculations. Closer inspection revealed that many variables contained a large proportion of zeros, creating a feature space where most observations were effectively equidistant, violating the assumptions of distance-based algorithms. This resulted in near-zero eigenvalues in the model matrix, making the data highly unstable for clustering.

Additionally, skewed distributions and potential outliers further distorted the feature space.Applying the Yeo-Johnson transformation helped reduce skewness across many variables, improving spacing between observations and making the data more suitable for clustering. This process reinforced the importance of thorough exploratory data analysis and thoughtful transformation before applying clustering techniques.

Among the methods tested, DBSCAN offered the most meaningful segmentation, revealing more nuanced clusters without needing to predefine the number of groups. It also aligned closely with engagement levels, making it a strong choice for interpreting user behavior and identifying opportunities for action.

To further understand what drives conversion, user journey flows were compared between high-intent browsers and deliberate shoppers. While both groups engaged with key product and catalog pages, deliberate shoppers moved through the funnel more smoothly and made use of supporting tools like wishlists and info pages. In contrast, high-intent browsers were more likely to hit friction points, including error and request pages.

Drawing from these patterns, the following recommendations highlight areas where targeted improvements could enhance user experience and boost conversions:

  • Streamline the shopping path: Strengthen connections between product and checkout pages. Make helpful tools like wishlists and info pages more visible to support decision-making.
  • Reduce friction for high-intent users: Investigate common pain points such as error and request pages. These may be causing unnecessary drop-offs, even among users showing strong interest.
  • Tailor follow-ups based on behavior: Use cluster insights to inform personalized re-engagement strategies. For example, prompt high-intent users with reminders or nudges tailored to their previous browsing behavior.
  • Keep monitoring for shifts: Re-run clustering periodically to track evolving user behavior. New campaigns, site changes, or seasonality could shift how users navigate and convert.

While this analysis offers a strong starting point, there’s room for deeper exploration. Future work could incorporate additional behavioral signals or alternative modeling approaches to further refine segmentation and support more adaptive, personalized strategies.

Appendix¶

A. Distribution of Engagement Level by Geographic Continent¶

The distribution of engagement levels remains relatively stable across geographic regions. In all continents, passive sessions comprise the majority, followed by engaged users, with purchasers representing a small proportion. These patterns indicate that geo_continent does not provide substantial differentiation in user behavior and thus was excluded from downstream modeling.
